                "img": "https://arxiv.org/html/2603.02578/2603.02578v1/x1.png",
                "caption": "Figure 1:Behavioral control targets can be organized by granularity.\nFor example, the target ofautonomyprogresses from a high-level objective (Level 1), to a constrained manner of expression (Level 2), and finally to a directly checkable surface realization (Level 3).",
                "position": 330
            },
            {
                "img": "https://arxiv.org/html/2603.02578/2603.02578v1/figures/data_examples.jpg",
                "caption": "Figure 2:Example cases from the three domainsPersonality,Sentiment, andLanguage Featuresacross the L1∼\\simL3 hierarchies.\nTakingLanguage Featuresas an example, the core steering goal is to increase redundancy.\nAtLevel 1 (L1), the model is guided to express the general intent “Increase redundancy”, shifting from “Concise phrasing” to “Elaborative repetition”.\nAtLevel 2 (L2), the steering specifies a strategy for realization, moving from a “Single expression” to a “Rephrased restatement”.\nAtLevel 3 (L3), atomic, verifiable markers are enforced, requiring the inclusion of “(i.e.,”.\nThese examples illustrate how each level progressively constrains model outputs from abstract intent to concrete surface evidence.\nFurther details are provided in §3.",
                "position": 357
            }
        ]
